@RobTrades139 Some jobs will still be there, but 90-95% will be gone. Elon also knows this of course, but he focuses on the positive aspects (abundance and UHI).

No, because AI replaces intelligence, that only thing that made humans really unique. It's not about automating a skill, but replacing anything a human can do. The Internet led to new opportunities, AI will be able to do those opportunities itself. There will be many one person companies, but not a lot of companies that will hire people.

I think the US will invest in the whole AI production chain, not just the LLMs. At this point only the US and China have a full AI stack, I don't see other countries developing them anytime soon, especially not frontier models. That means the RoW will likely use US and Chinese models, not local ones. Hard to predict now how this will play out of course, but my AI investments are in the whole stack, and both in China and the US.

@CN10245574 Based on my own experience in running an AI company, I think the odds are at least 80% that most jobs will be gone eventually. The main question is the time line and how governments react (they could for example put huge taxes on AI and on robots)
